/* casestudies2.js — case studies 12–22 */
(function (D) {
  'use strict';
  D.caseStudies = (D.caseStudies || []).concat([

  { id: 'cs12', title: 'Transaction-Monitoring Platform', difficulty: 'Expert', banking: true,
    problem: `Design AML transaction monitoring: detect suspicious behaviour patterns (structuring, layering, velocity anomalies) across 10M transactions/day, generate alerts into case management, support SAR filing — with every detection decision reproducible for the regulator.`,
    clarifying: ['Scenario catalogue: how many typologies, rule vs model mix?', 'Detection latency tiers (real-time patterns vs 90-day aggregations)?', 'Alert volumes and analyst capacity?', 'Backtesting expectations when logic changes?', 'Data sources beyond transactions (customer risk, relationships)?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** ingest posted transactions + customer context; run versioned detection scenarios (rules + models); dedupe/correlate alerts; case workflow with SAR path; tuning with backtests; coverage reporting against typologies.\n**NFR:** near-real-time tier < 5 min for high-risk patterns; daily batch tier for aggregation scenarios; every alert reproducible (inputs, logic version); tipping-off confidentiality; 10 y evidence.\n**Volumes:** 10M tx/day; expected alert rate ~0.1% pre-reduction; analysts can work ~2k/day.`,
    scale: `10M/day ≈ 120/s average, 500/s peak — comfortable streaming. The real maths: 10k raw alerts/day vs 2k analyst capacity → **the false-positive-reduction layer is a hard requirement, not an optimisation**. 90-day-window scenarios need stateful aggregation or warehouse jobs — tier accordingly.`,
    options: `1. Nightly SQL per scenario: misses the real-time tier, unmanageable at 100+ scenarios.\n2. Streaming (Kafka Streams/Flink) + batch tier + governed scenario registry: matches the latency mix.\n3. Vendor TM suite: strong typology coverage, weak on your data richness; the lab-25 analysis applies — assume hybrid outcome here (owned pipeline, vendor scenario content licensed).`,
    recommended: `Ingest transaction.events.v1 (keyed accountId) enriched with customer risk/relationship context (event-fed local views) → **two detection tiers**: streaming jobs for velocity/real-time patterns (stateful, windowed, keyed by account/party), nightly batch for long-window aggregations (warehouse-side, same scenario registry) → alerts (scored, deduped, correlated per party) → **case management** (reusing the cs11 platform's workflow: one case per correlated alert-group, four-eyes on closure, SAR generation with confidentiality walls) → **scenario registry**: every rule/model versioned, approved, backtested before deploy; every alert carries scenario-version + input snapshot hash.`,
    tradeoffs: `Two tiers double the runtime surface but match physics (you cannot stream a 90-day aggregation sensibly, nor batch a real-time pattern). The false-positive reduction (scoring, suppression rules) trades recall risk — governed like a model, compliance-owned thresholds, backtested. Vendor scenario content trades some fit for regulator-recognised typology coverage.`,
    dataApis: `Entities: Scenario(version, tier, params), Alert(scenario-version, inputs-hash, score), CaseLink, SuppressionRule(versioned!), SARRecord. APIs: analyst worklists, alert drill-down (full input reconstruction), tuning workbench (backtest runner), coverage reports.`,
    kafka: `Consumes transaction/customer/relationship events; alerts.v1 keyed by partyId (correlation locality); suppressions audited as events; detection state stores changelog-backed (rebuildable).`,
    security: `Tipping-off: SAR existence visible only to a walled role; detection logic confidential (coded alert reasons outward); insider threat on suppression rules (four-eyes on rule changes — a suppression rule is a hole by design).`,
    failures: `Streaming state loss → rebuild from changelog topics + replay window (idempotent alert emission on scenario+entity+window keys — replays must not re-alert). Late/out-of-order transactions → watermark tolerance; beyond-window arrivals route to batch catch-up. Enrichment view stale → alerts flagged with context-version; material staleness pauses high-risk scenarios (alert-on-absence monitoring). Scenario deploy bug → per-scenario kill switch + backtest gate should have caught it; alerts from the bad version quarantined by version tag.`,
    operations: `Alert-rate per scenario trended (drift = model/world change); analyst queue ageing; backtest-before-deploy as pipeline gate; coverage matrix (typology → scenarios) maintained for the regulator.`,
    migration: `Shadow-run against the legacy TM for two quarters — the comparison is both validation evidence and tuning data; scenario-by-scenario cutover; legacy alerts' case history migrated read-only.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: two-tier detection (latency physics). ADR-2: scenario registry with backtest gates (model governance). ADR-3: alert reproducibility via input snapshots (evidence cost accepted).`,
    followups: ['An alert fired last March under scenario v12 — reconstruct it.', 'How do you prove coverage of a new FATF typology?', 'Suppression rules cut alerts 40% — what is the governance around that number?'],
    rubric: ['Alert-volume vs analyst-capacity maths done', 'Tiering by window physics', 'Everything versioned: scenarios, suppressions, inputs', 'Replay-safe alert emission', 'Tipping-off walls designed'] },

  { id: 'cs13', title: 'Real-Time Fraud-Detection Platform', difficulty: 'Expert', banking: true,
    problem: `Design in-flight fraud detection on the payment path (cs9's fraud-check box, opened up): score every payment in ≤ 150 ms, block/step-up/allow, learn from outcomes, survive its own outages safely — the rv10 review scenario done right.`,
    clarifying: ['Latency budget within the payment SLA?', 'Decision actions available (block, step-up, hold, allow)?', 'Model governance regime (validation, approvals)?', 'Label sources (confirmed fraud, disputes) and their lag?', 'Rules vs model split appetite?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** real-time scoring (features + model + rules), decisioning with reason codes, case creation for review-tier, feedback ingestion (outcomes → labels), champion/challenger model rollout, threshold governance.\n**NFR:** p99 ≤ 150 ms in-line; fail-safe degraded mode (never silent fail-open); every decision reproducible (features, model + threshold versions); drift monitoring; 99.99% availability of the decision function.\n**Volumes:** 400/s peak payments; feature store reads 3× that.`,
    scale: `150 ms budget decomposes: feature fetch ≤ 30 ms (precomputed aggregates in a low-latency store), model inference ≤ 50 ms, rules + decision ≤ 20 ms, margin for transport. The budget arithmetic **forbids** synchronous core-DB feature queries — the rv10 lesson.`,
    options: `1. Batch-scored risk lists checked at payment time: cheap, blind to in-flight patterns.\n2. Real-time features + online inference + rules overlay: the target.\n3. Vendor fraud engine: viable; scored on data richness and lock-in; assume build-on-platform here with vendor consortium-data enrichment.`,
    recommended: `**Feature platform**: streaming jobs (consuming payment/transaction/session events) maintain per-account/party/device aggregates (velocity, geo-patterns) in a replicated low-latency store; features versioned with lineage. **Decision service**: stateless, horizontally scaled, loads model versions from a registry; evaluates governed rules + model score → decision (allow/step-up/review/block) with reason codes; champion/challenger runs challengers in shadow. **Feedback loop**: dispute/chargeback/confirmed-fraud events label historical decisions; drift monitors compare live score distributions vs training baselines. **Governance**: models and thresholds versioned, approved, backtested; every decision logs feature-vector hash + versions (storage is cheaper than an unexplainable block).`,
    tradeoffs: `Precomputed features trade freshness (seconds of lag on aggregates) for the latency budget — in-flight payment attributes cover the gap. Champion/challenger doubles inference cost for safe evolution. The review tier trades friction for recall — its size is a staffed-capacity decision, not an engineering constant.`,
    dataApis: `Entities: FeatureView(version), ModelVersion(registry), Decision(features-hash, versions, reasons), Label, ThresholdPolicy(versioned, approved). APIs: POST /score (the 150 ms contract), decision lookup, case handoff to investigation, tuning workbench.`,
    kafka: `Consumes payment/transaction/session streams; decisions.v1 keyed by paymentId (audit spine + label joining); labels.v1; feature-store changelogs (rebuildable). Decision path itself is synchronous — Kafka feeds it, never sits in it.`,
    security: `Reason codes outward-facing coded (no logic leakage — fraudsters probe); model/threshold changes four-eyes; feature store contains behavioural PII (classification, access audit, retention); adversarial testing (GPS/device spoofing patterns) in the test regime.`,
    failures: `Decision service degraded → **conservative rules-only fallback + loud alerting + flagged decisions** (rv10's fix): fail-safe, never silent fail-open. Feature store stale → decisions flag context-age; beyond threshold, tighten to rules-tier. Model rollout bad → challenger gates + instant version rollback (registry). Score distribution drifts → alert, freeze auto-actions above severity, human review widens.`,
    operations: `SLIs: decision p99, fallback-mode minutes (target 0, alarmed), block/step-up rates per version (step-changes = investigate), label lag. Every threshold change is a governed release with backtest evidence.`,
    migration: `Shadow-score for a quarter (no actions) → step-up-only actions → full decisioning, gated on precision/recall evidence vs the incumbent rules.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: precomputed feature platform (budget arithmetic). ADR-2: fail-safe rules fallback (rv10). ADR-3: full decision reproducibility (regulatory model governance).`,
    followups: ['Walk a disputed block from customer call to reconstructed decision.', 'How does step-up authentication change the fraud economics vs blocking?', 'The challenger outperforms on fraud but blocks 2× more good payments — decide.'],
    rubric: ['Latency budget decomposed and enforced', 'Fail-safe (not fail-open) degradation', 'Model + threshold governance versioned', 'Feedback/label loop designed', 'Reproducible decisions'] },

  { id: 'cs14', title: 'Customer Master-Data Platform', difficulty: 'Advanced', banking: true,
    problem: `Build the bank's party/customer master (bk47 expanded): one golden source for party identity feeding screening, payments, CRM and reporting — consolidating three legacy "masters" that disagree about 15% of records.`,
    clarifying: ['Attribute survivorship rules — who wins per field?', 'Merge governance: auto vs steward thresholds?', 'The 15% disagreement: profiled? categories?', 'Consumer freshness needs per domain?', 'GDPR/banking-secrecy overlay per attribute class?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** ingest from channels/legacy; match/merge with steward workflow; survivorship per attribute; distribute via events + APIs; history ("what did we believe on date X"); merge/unmerge with full audit.\n**NFR:** no silent auto-merge of distinct persons (a wrong merge = wrong-party screening/payments); event freshness ≤ 60 s to consumers; 10 y history; erasure per attribute class where law allows.\n**Volumes:** 3M parties, 40k changes/day, initial consolidation of 4.2M source records → ~3M golden.`,
    scale: `Change velocity is trivial; the consolidation is the project: 4.2M records, ~15% conflicting → ~600k conflict cases, auto-resolvable maybe 80% by survivorship rules → **120k steward decisions**: the human pipeline is the critical path, size it (20 stewards × 100/day ≈ 60 working days).`,
    options: `1. Pick one legacy master and force the others to conform: fast, enshrines its defects.\n2. New golden source with match/merge + survivorship: the real MDM.\n3. Virtual/federated master (registry pointing at sources): lighter, but consumers still reconcile three truths.`,
    recommended: `Option 2. **Matching**: deterministic keys (verified IDs) first, probabilistic (name+DOB+address scoring) second; confidence thresholds route: high → auto-link, medium → steward queue, low → distinct. **Survivorship**: per-attribute precedence rules, versioned (verified-channel beats batch-import beats CRM), every applied rule recorded. **Distribution**: customer.events.v1 (outbox) + query APIs; consumers keep derived copies. **History**: bitemporal (valid-time + knowledge-time) — "what did we believe on date X" is a regulator question with a query answer. **Merge/unmerge**: full audit, downstream notification events, and the unmerge path designed BEFORE go-live (wrong merges happen; cs-follow-up drills it).`,
    tradeoffs: `A new master costs consolidation pain once vs conformity to defects forever. Bitemporal storage doubles complexity for evidence-grade history — banking justifies it; the ADR says so with the query list. Steward-gated merges trade throughput for the no-wrong-merge guarantee — the queue is staffed accordingly.`,
    dataApis: `Party(golden, bitemporal), SourceLink(party↔source records), MatchDecision(score, rule-version, steward?), SurvivorshipRule(versioned), MergeEvent. APIs: party read (entitlement-scoped field masking), search, steward workbench, lineage per attribute ("this address came from source X on date Y via rule Z").`,
    kafka: `customer.events.v1 keyed partyId (the estate's most-consumed topic — schema governance strictest here); merge/unmerge events with old→new ID mappings (consumers MUST handle re-keying — a published contract obligation); consumes legacy CDC during migration.`,
    security: `The master is the crown-jewel PII store: field-level entitlements, access audit, per-attribute classification driving masking; erasure per class with legal-hold overrides; banking-secrecy jurisdictional views (bk13 patterns).`,
    failures: `Wrong merge discovered post-transactions → unmerge workflow: split records, reassign source links, emit re-key events, downstream reconciliation verifies (screening re-scoped, payments history attributed) — rehearsed, audited. Legacy feed sends garbage → quarantine + steward triage, never auto-applied to golden. Event consumer misses re-key → the periodic full-sync reconciliation (b7) catches divergence.`,
    operations: `Data-quality dashboards (completeness, conflict rates per source), steward queue SLAs, merge/unmerge rates trended (rising wrong-merges = matching-rule drift), consumer lag.`,
    migration: `Profile first (the 15% becomes categories with rules); consolidate segment-by-segment with steward capacity as the pacing constraint; legacy masters demoted to consumers via CDC-fed conformance, then retired on dates; every phase's reconciliation (golden vs legacy) published as evidence.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: new golden source over conformance (defect analysis attached). ADR-2: bitemporal history (regulator queries listed). ADR-3: steward-gated medium-confidence merges (wrong-merge cost dominates).`,
    followups: ['Two customers wrongly merged transacted for a month — unwind it end-to-end.', 'A consumer wants "just a nightly full extract" — response?', 'Which attribute\'s survivorship rule would compliance and marketing fight over?'],
    rubric: ['Consolidation maths incl. human pipeline', 'Survivorship + matching versioned and governed', 'Bitemporal history justified by queries', 'Unmerge designed before go-live', 'Re-key contract obligation on consumers'] },

  { id: 'cs15', title: 'Partner & Business-Relationship Platform', difficulty: 'Advanced', banking: true,
    problem: `Design the relationship domain (bx17 expanded): typed, dated party-to-party relationships, roles, and UBO traversal — the data screening scope depends on, currently scattered across five systems as foreign keys and spreadsheets.`,
    clarifying: ['Relationship types in scope (ownership, control, representation, guarantees)?', 'UBO thresholds per jurisdiction?', 'Data quality reality of existing sources?', 'Who may assert a relationship (channels, stewards, documents)?', 'Freshness needs of screening scope recomputation?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** relationship CRUD with evidence attachments; typed roles with validity periods; UBO traversal (effective ownership, jurisdiction rules); event publication for scope consumers; steward workflows for conflicting assertions.\n**NFR:** traversal correct and reproducible (evidence per computation); relationship changes propagate to screening ≤ 5 min; history complete; the graph queryable ad hoc by investigators.\n**Volumes:** 3M parties, ~1.2M relationships, 5k changes/day, chains to depth 8 observed.`,
    scale: `Modest volumes — the complexity is semantic (types, validity, jurisdiction rules) and topological (chains, cycles — yes, cycles: A owns B owns C owns A through funds; the traversal must terminate and flag). Store choice: graph DB earns its place if investigator ad-hoc traversal is real; recursive SQL suffices for the computed UBO pipeline — the honest answer may be both (SoR relational, graph as derived exploration view).`,
    options: `1. Relationship tables inside the party master: couples two domains with different cadences/consumers (b6's argument for separation).\n2. Dedicated relationship domain, relational SoR + derived graph view: recommended.\n3. Graph DB as SoR: traversal-native but weaker on the audit/constraint posture the SoR needs.`,
    recommended: `Dedicated domain: relational SoR (relationships with type, share, validity, evidence-refs, assertion source) with constraint-enforced invariants; **UBO computation service**: versioned jurisdiction rule sets, traversal with cycle detection, outputs BeneficialOwnerUpdated (uboSetVersion — set semantics per the event catalogue) with the full computation evidence (chain, shares, rule version) retained; **derived graph view** (Neo4j-style) rebuilt from events for investigator exploration — rebuildable, never authoritative. Events: RelationshipCreated/Expired/PartnerRoleChanged keyed by subjectPartyId (per-party scope-recomputation ordering).`,
    tradeoffs: `Two stores (relational + graph) cost sync machinery for fit-per-workload — the rebuildable-derived discipline keeps it honest. Set-semantics UBO events (replace whole set per version) trade payload size for consumer simplicity and idempotency — deltas invite ordering bugs in exactly the flow that must not have them.`,
    dataApis: `Relationship(subject, object, type, share, validFrom/To, evidence, source), RoleAssignment, UboComputation(inputs, rule-version, result, timestamp). APIs: relationship assertion (with evidence), party relationship view, UBO query (as-of capable), investigator graph queries, steward conflict queue.`,
    kafka: `relationship.events.v1 per the catalogue (restricted — ownership data is confidential); BeneficialOwnerUpdated consumed by screening (EDD triggers), reporting; consumes party merge/re-key events from cs14 (relationships survive party merges — the integration test that matters).`,
    security: `Ownership structures are competitively and legally sensitive: restricted topic ACLs, field-level access, full access audit; assertion provenance (who claimed this relationship, on what document) is evidence, not metadata.`,
    failures: `Cycle in ownership → traversal terminates, flags for steward review, UBO output marked partial (screening treats partial as EDD-trigger — fail toward more diligence). Conflicting assertions (two sources disagree on share) → steward queue, both retained with provenance, golden view marks disputed. Missed relationship event downstream → the bx-standard reconciliation: active relationships vs screening scopes, both directions. Party merge upstream → re-key handling verified by post-merge reconciliation.`,
    operations: `Scope-propagation lag SLI (the 5-min promise); disputed-relationship queue ageing; UBO recomputation volumes after rule changes (a jurisdiction rule change = mass recompute = mini list-update event, planned like one).`,
    migration: `Source-by-source ingestion with provenance; the spreadsheet era's data enters via steward-validated batches; five legacy FK-webs retire per source as consumers move to the domain's events/APIs.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: dedicated domain separate from party master (cadence, consumers, sensitivity). ADR-2: relational SoR + derived graph (workload fit with rebuild discipline). ADR-3: set-semantics UBO events (idempotency over payload economy).`,
    followups: ['A 40% + 25%-indirect owner — compute the effective ownership and its evidence.', 'A jurisdiction lowers the UBO threshold to 10% — operational impact?', 'Why must partial traversals fail toward EDD rather than toward "clear"?'],
    rubric: ['Domain separation argued from cadence/consumers', 'Cycle and conflict handling designed', 'UBO evidence reproducible with rule versions', 'Set-semantics idempotency reasoning', 'Merge/re-key integration handled'] },

  { id: 'cs16', title: 'Regulatory-Reporting Platform', difficulty: 'Advanced', banking: true,
    problem: `Design the platform producing the bank's regulatory reports (bk48 expanded): dozens of periodic reports from shared data, each point-in-time correct, lineage-traceable, deadline-bound — replacing a wilderness of SQL scripts and spreadsheets owned by whoever wrote them.`,
    clarifying: ['Report inventory: count, frequencies, deadlines, formats?', 'Restatement/resubmission rules per regulator?', 'Bitemporal needs ("as known on date X")?', 'Source-system data-quality reality?', 'Sign-off workflow before submission?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** versioned data ingestion (snapshots or bitemporal store); calculation pipelines versioned like code; report generation per regulator format; sign-off workflow (maker-checker); controlled resubmission with difference audit; lineage per figure.\n**NFR:** any report rerunnable byte-identical (same inputs + logic); deadlines with late-START alerting; lineage to source within 24 h of a query; 10 y retention of reports + inputs + logic versions.\n**Volumes:** ~60 reports, daily to quarterly; largest consumes 200M rows.`,
    scale: `The batch-graph is the system: dependency-ordered pipelines with deadline-derived scheduling (a 06:00 submission means late-start alerts at each upstream stage — b9 discipline). The 200M-row report sizes the compute tier; everything else rides along.`,
    options: `1. Modern BI on the warehouse: queries yes, reproducibility/sign-off/lineage no.\n2. Versioned pipeline platform (ingestion snapshots + dbt-style versioned transforms + orchestration): recommended.\n3. Vendor reg-reporting suite: strong formats, weak on your source integration; scored per a5 — often lands as hybrid (vendor for formats/submission, owned pipeline beneath).`,
    recommended: `**Ingestion**: per-source versioned snapshots (or CDC into a bitemporal store where "as known" queries demand it) — inputs are immutable, identified, retained. **Calculation**: transforms versioned in git, deployed as releases; a report run = (input versions × logic version) recorded → reruns are byte-identical by construction. **Orchestration**: dependency graph with deadline-back-calculated schedules, late-start alerting, rerun tooling. **Lineage**: captured from the pipeline automatically (not documented by hand — mo3's fiction warning). **Sign-off**: maker-checker workflow gating submission; **resubmission**: a new versioned run linked to the original with a difference report — regulators ask what changed and why.`,
    tradeoffs: `Immutable input snapshots cost storage (priced: cheap vs one failed audit); bitemporality applied selectively (reports needing "as known" — not everything). The versioned-release discipline slows hotfixes deliberately: a fixed report is a NEW version with a difference trail, never an edit — the spreadsheet era's unlearning.`,
    dataApis: `Entities: SourceSnapshot(version), TransformRelease(version), ReportRun(inputs, logic, output-hash), SignOff(maker, checker), Resubmission(diff). APIs: run status, lineage query (figure → sources), sign-off workbench, evidence retrieval.`,
    kafka: `Ingestion via CDC/events from source domains; run-lifecycle events for orchestration/alerting; the platform is batch-hearted — Kafka feeds it, deadlines drive it.`,
    security: `Report data spans the bank's most aggregated sensitive figures: access on need-to-know, sign-off identities audited, submission channels authenticated; the tampering threat (adjusting a figure pre-submission) countered by output hashing + immutable run records.`,
    failures: `Source late → late-start alert fires hours before the deadline is at risk (the b9 point: alert on schedule deviation, not just failure); pipeline failure → checkpointed rerun; wrong figure discovered post-submission → controlled resubmission workflow with diff + root cause; source restates ITS data → downstream runs re-executed with new input versions, both retained ("we reported X on date D based on inputs I" stays provable).`,
    operations: `The deadline wall: every report's countdown, stage ETAs, late-start ambers. Rerun capacity reserved (reruns cluster at quarter-end, when capacity is scarcest — plan it).`,
    migration: `Report-by-report: rebuild in the platform, parallel-run against the legacy script until identical (or differences explained and signed), then the script retires; the highest-risk reports first is tempting but wrong — start mid-risk to learn safely.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: immutable input versioning (reproducibility by construction). ADR-2: selective bitemporality (cost honesty). ADR-3: resubmission-as-new-version (evidence discipline).`,
    followups: ['The regulator queries one figure from Q3 two years ago — walk the trace.', 'A source system restates last month\'s data — cascade the consequences.', 'Why start migration with mid-risk reports?'],
    rubric: ['Reproducibility by construction (inputs × logic versions)', 'Deadline-aware operations with late-start alerts', 'Automated lineage', 'Resubmission with difference evidence', 'Migration parallel-run discipline'] },

  { id: 'cs17', title: 'Banking Audit & Evidence Platform', difficulty: 'Advanced', banking: true,
    problem: `Design the central audit domain (bx15 expanded): every domain's audit events, immutably stored, retrievable as evidence for a decade — the platform every other case study emits into.`,
    clarifying: ['Event volume across the estate?', 'Integrity requirements: hash-chaining? WORM mandates?', 'Retrieval patterns: investigations, regulator requests, litigation holds?', 'Retention per event category (min AND max)?', 'Who audits the auditors (access to audit data)?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** ingest audit events against a published contract; immutable storage with integrity verification; retrieval by entity/actor/time/correlation; litigation holds; retention automation per category; completeness monitoring (detect domains that stopped emitting).\n**NFR:** ingestion never blocks producers; zero event loss post-acknowledgement (RPO 0); integrity provable (tamper-evidence); retrieval SLA 24 h for regulator requests; 7–10 y retention with automated expiry where law permits.\n**Volumes:** ~50M events/day estate-wide.`,
    scale: `50M/day ≈ 600/s average — Kafka-shaped ingestion; the storage maths dominates: ~50M × 1 KB × 365 × 10 y ≈ 180 TB → tiered storage (hot 90 d, warm 2 y, cold archive) with retrieval capability at every tier (archived ≠ inaccessible — the bx7 lesson).`,
    options: `1. Every domain keeps its own audit tables: completeness unverifiable, retention 12 ways, system-replacement loses evidence — the status quo being replaced.\n2. Central platform with published contract: recommended.\n3. Vendor GRC/archive suite: storage yes, contract/integration no — hybrid possible for the WORM tier.`,
    recommended: `**Contract**: audit-event schema (actor, action, authority, entity refs, data versions, correlation ID, source domain) — publishing it is a governance act; fitness checks verify every regulated service emits (the "forgot to audit" class fails builds, b6). **Ingestion**: audit.events.v1 (producers use outbox — audit of a change must share its fate); platform consumes with RPO-0 posture: sync-replicated append-only store, hash-chained per stream (tamper evidence), periodic integrity verification jobs. **Retrieval**: indexed views (by entity, actor, correlation) as rebuildable read models over the immutable core; investigation workbench; litigation-hold flags overriding expiry. **Retention**: category schedules automated; deletion (where law permits) via crypto-shredding or verified purge, itself audited.`,
    tradeoffs: `Central platform is a single point of evidence — hence the RPO-0 sync replication and integrity jobs (priced; the store is append-only and compresses well). The published contract constrains domains (schema evolution governance) — the alternative is 12 informal formats and no completeness story. Hash-chaining adds write-path cost for tamper-evidence; scoped to streams where non-repudiation matters most.`,
    dataApis: `AuditEvent(contract), StreamCheckpoint(hash-chain anchors), Hold, RetentionSchedule. APIs: emit (via Kafka, not sync API — producer isolation), query (entitled, audited), hold management (legal), completeness dashboards.`,
    kafka: `audit.events.v1 keyed by source-domain+entity (locality without global hotspots — the lab-13 trick question applied); consumes from every domain; the platform's own access events feed BACK into it (the auditors are audited).`,
    security: `Access to audit data is the insider-threat crown jewel: strict entitlements, four-eyes on bulk exports, every query itself audited; integrity verification scheduled and alarmed; the admin plane behind PAM.`,
    failures: `Platform ingestion down → Kafka buffers (producers unaffected — the isolation requirement); extended outage → completeness reconciliation on recovery verifies no gaps. A domain silently stops emitting → completeness monitoring (expected-volume baselines per domain) alerts — absence is the signal (gx27). Integrity check fails → incident of the highest order: scoped forensics via chain anchors, regulator communication per counsel.`,
    operations: `Completeness dashboards per domain (the product for compliance); retrieval SLA tracking; storage-tier economics reviewed; restore-from-archive rehearsed (evidence you cannot retrieve is evidence you do not have).`,
    migration: `Domains onboard incrementally (contract adapters); legacy audit tables either migrated with integrity verification or retained read-only to their retention end — both paths evidenced.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: central platform with published contract (completeness verifiability). ADR-2: RPO-0 scoped here (evidence loss is unacceptable; the store is small enough). ADR-3: Kafka-mediated emission (producer isolation over sync-API simplicity).`,
    followups: ['Prove domain X emitted completely last month.', 'Legal requests a litigation hold across three entities — walk the mechanics.', 'Why is the audit platform\'s OWN access log its most sensitive stream?'],
    rubric: ['Producer isolation via buffered ingestion', 'Integrity + completeness both engineered', 'Retention automation with hold overrides', 'Tiered storage with retrieval at every tier', 'The auditors-audited loop closed'] },

  { id: 'cs18', title: 'Legacy Banking Monolith Modernisation', difficulty: 'Expert', banking: true,
    problem: `A 19-year-old branch-banking monolith (the rv9 review scenario, done right this time): plan and architect its modernisation into the b6 domain landscape without a big bang, without a change freeze, and without a weekend that ends careers.`,
    clarifying: ['Which capabilities hurt most (change frequency × pain)?', 'Data quality and schema archaeology status?', 'Team availability and domain knowledge distribution?', 'Regulatory continuity requirements during migration?', 'What may legitimately DIE rather than migrate?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** full capability continuity during migration; slice-by-slice extraction into the domain landscape; feature-change capability throughout (no freeze).\n**NFR:** zero regulatory-control gaps mid-migration (audit, screening, reporting continue provably); per-slice rollback until reconciliation-clean; the monolith's EOD dependencies honoured until replaced.\n**Constraints:** 3 teams initially, scaling with validated boundaries; 3-year horizon with value milestones, not a 3-year cliff.`,
    scale: `The monolith: ~2M LOC, 400 tables, 200 batch jobs, 40 integrations. The archaeology (mapping tables/jobs to future domains) is months of work and the honest first deliverable — you cannot slice what you have not mapped.`,
    options: `1. Big-bang rewrite (rv9's corpse, dissected there).\n2. Strangler by business capability with event-first seams: recommended.\n3. Buy a core-satellite suite and migrate onto it: legitimate for some capabilities — the per-domain sourcing question recurs inside option 2 anyway.`,
    recommended: `**Phase 0 (months 1–4)**: archaeology (capability→code→table→job mapping), event storming with the business (the boundaries come from language, not the schema), characterisation tests around the top flows, CI + facade routing infrastructure. **Slicing strategy**: first slice = party/customer READ path (high reuse, low risk — a read model fed by CDC from the monolith's tables through a transform ACL); then notification (low coupling); then party WRITE ownership (the first real data-ownership transfer, with parallel-run reconciliation); payments LAST. **Per slice**: one-writer-per-entity decided, CDC or API coexistence with retirement date, reconciliation until clean, rollback until reconciliation-clean, controls continuity checked (audit events flow from EITHER side throughout — the regulator does not accept gaps). **The ledger core**: evaluated honestly — likely remains a modular monolith heart (d9/bk5) with domains extracted around it; "everything must become microservices" is not a requirement anyone stated.`,
    tradeoffs: `Slice-by-slice trades total duration (longer) for risk shape (each slice reversible) — the rv9 lesson priced. CDC-from-legacy couples new services to old schema temporarily (transform ACLs contain it; retirement dates enforce it). No-freeze means merge-friction between BAU and migration — branch-by-abstraction seams and the characterisation tests are the friction budget.`,
    dataApis: `Per-slice contracts as they extract (the b6 landscape emerging); the facade's routing table is versioned configuration with an owner; the archaeology map is a living artifact (application landscape + capability map, mo3).`,
    kafka: `The event backbone lands early (phase 0 infrastructure): CDC topics (transformed, versioned) feed read models; as domains take write ownership their proper domain events replace CDC feeds — the CDC-to-domain-event transition per slice is a designed contract migration (k3 discipline).`,
    security: `The facade is new attack surface (harden it); legacy credentials/secrets get vaulted during phase 0 (cheap win); per-slice threat models as boundaries move; the monolith's shared-DB access list SHRINKS as slices extract (measurable security improvement per slice).`,
    failures: `Slice reconciliation dirty → rollback via facade, investigate, retry — designed, rehearsed, boring. Monolith EOD job breaks post-slice → the archaeology map + job-dependency graph makes it diagnosable; batch continuity is a per-slice checklist item. Team knowledge gap on a weird flow → the last-20% inventory (m2) exists from phase 0; weird flows get decided (migrate/rebuild/retire) not discovered.`,
    operations: `Migration dashboards: slices in flight, reconciliation status, facade routing state, monolith shrinkage (LOC/tables retired — the demotivation antidote); dual-run cost tracked and time-boxed per slice.`,
    migration: `This case study IS the migration plan; rollback per slice as above; the programme's end state includes the honest possibility that the ledger heart stays put — success = pressure-driven extraction complete, not extinction.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: strangler over big-bang (rv9 analysis attached). ADR-2: read-path-first slicing (learning value ordering). ADR-3: ledger heart retained pending real pressure (d9). ADR-4: CDC coexistence with dated retirement per slice.`,
    followups: ['Which slice would you re-order under deadline pressure, and which never?', 'The business demands a new lending feature mid-migration — where does it land?', 'Prove to the regulator that audit continuity held during slice 3.'],
    rubric: ['Archaeology before slicing', 'Boundaries from event storming, not schema', 'Per-slice data ownership + reconciliation + rollback', 'Controls continuity as explicit requirement', 'Honest end state (ledger heart may remain)'] },

  { id: 'cs19', title: 'On-Premises to Cloud Migration', difficulty: 'Advanced', banking: true,
    problem: `Migrate a bank's 200-application estate to cloud within 3 years (data-centre lease expiry — a real deadline), with residency constraints, regulator expectations (exit plans, controls), and the rv4 lift-and-shift cautionary tale in recent memory.`,
    clarifying: ['Lease drop-dead date and DC exit penalties?', 'Residency/jurisdiction map of the estate\'s data?', 'Regulator posture on cloud (approvals, exit-plan expectations)?', 'Current landing-zone maturity (rv4 suggests: none)?', 'Portfolio skew: how many apps are 80% of the risk?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** all 200 applications dispositioned (6R triage) and executed; DC exited by lease end.\n**NFR:** no availability regression per app tier; residency honoured per data class; landing-zone guardrails before workload one; tested exit plans for material workloads (regulator); cost model per wave (no rv4 surprise bills).\n**Constraints:** the core banking system's disposition is its own programme (cs18) — this programme owns everything else.`,
    scale: `200 apps: triage typically lands ~40% rehost, 30% replatform, 10% refactor, 10% replace(SaaS), 10% retire — the retire slice is free money (find it first). Wave planning: ~20 apps/quarter after wave one proves the machinery.`,
    options: `1. Lift-and-shift everything fast (rv4 at estate scale).\n2. Landing zone first, then triaged waves by risk/value: recommended.\n3. Refactor-everything: the lease expires before the third app is beautiful.`,
    recommended: `**Foundation (quarters 1–2)**: landing zone (c1's five components — accounts, hub-spoke networks with egress-deny, identity federation, policy-as-code guardrails incl. residency-pinning rules, central logging), FinOps tagging standards, and the migration factory (runbooks, tooling, a practiced team). **Wave 1 (quarter 2)**: 10 low-risk apps proving the machinery end-to-end incl. one restore test and one rollback. **Waves 2–10**: triaged by (lease pressure × risk × value): rehost the stable middle (with rightsizing at migration — never copy on-prem sizes, rv4), replatform where managed services kill toil (DBs to managed, file drops to object storage), replace where SaaS won the a5 analysis, retire aggressively (every retired app is a migration you skip). **Residency**: data-classification map drives region pinning per app; guardrails enforce it (a policy, not a promise). **Exit plans**: per material workload, documented + rehearsed restore-elsewhere (c2's honest instrument), satisfying the regulator without symmetric multi-cloud theatre.`,
    tradeoffs: `Landing-zone-first spends two quarters "not migrating" — the alternative is rebuilding 200 apps' worth of mistakes (rv4 × 200, priced). Rehost-heavy triage trades cloud-native benefits for the lease deadline — with replatform-later flags on the candidates (the roadmap survives the deadline). Retirement fights app-owner attachment — executive air cover required and requested explicitly.`,
    dataApis: `The portfolio database IS the programme's data model: app, disposition, wave, dependencies, data classes, residency, owner, status — dependency mapping (mo4) drives wave composition (apps move with their chatty neighbours or pay latency/egress).`,
    kafka: `The estate's integration backbone migrates early (wave 1–2 infrastructure): cloud Kafka with mirroring from on-prem during transition — dual-run integration is the migration's circulatory system.`,
    security: `Guardrails before workloads (the whole point); per-wave threat-model deltas (what changed: exposure, identity, network); the DC-exit endgame is itself a security event (data destruction evidence from decommissioned hardware — auditors ask).`,
    failures: `App breaks post-move → wave-1-proven rollback path (DNS/traffic back to on-prem while the DC still exists — the deadline\'s hidden gift is a natural rollback window that CLOSES; late waves lose it, hence risk-ordered scheduling). Egress bill spike → FinOps alerts per wave, chatty-pair analysis (should have moved together). Residency near-miss (data class discovered late) → the classification map was wrong — stop, reclassify, the guardrail catches the redeploy.`,
    operations: `Wave dashboards (apps moved, cost vs model, incidents per wave); the DC shrink-down plan (racks consolidating as waves complete — physical logistics are real); steady-state FinOps operating from day one, not after the bill.`,
    migration: `This IS one; rollback narrows as the DC empties — communicated as a programme risk with dates.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: landing zone first (rv4 at scale, priced). ADR-2: rehost-heavy triage with replatform flags (deadline honesty). ADR-3: exit plans as rehearsed restores, not multi-cloud (c2).`,
    followups: ['Which 10 apps make wave 1 and why those?', 'The lease deadline moves 6 months earlier — what changes?', 'An app owner refuses retirement of their unused app — mechanics?'],
    rubric: ['Foundation-before-workloads with priced justification', 'Triage arithmetic incl. retirement hunting', 'Residency as enforced guardrail', 'Rollback window management across waves', 'Exit plans regulator-shaped but honest'] },

  { id: 'cs20', title: 'Commercial Vendor Replacement', difficulty: 'Advanced', banking: true,
    problem: `Replace the incumbent screening vendor (contract ends in 18 months; pricing doubled at renewal quote; the rv7 lock-in lessons apply retroactively): migrate matching, in-flight cases, and a decade of decision evidence to a new vendor without a screening gap.`,
    clarifying: ['What does the old contract actually grant at exit (export formats, assistance, timelines)?', 'Evidence portability: raw match data or PDFs?', 'Case-state migration: in-flight investigations?', 'Parallel-run budget (double licence months)?', 'What did we learn to demand in the NEW contract?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** new vendor integrated (the cs11 ACL earning its keep); historical evidence migrated or retained-accessible; in-flight cases transitioned; matching-quality validated before cutover.\n**NFR:** zero screening-coverage gap on any day; evidence continuity provable across the seam ("decisions before date D: old platform, after: new — both retrievable"); matching quality ≥ incumbent (measured, not assumed); the new contract exits better than the old one entered.\n**Constraint:** 18-month clock with the incumbent's cooperation decaying as it runs.`,
    scale: `3M parties re-baselined against the new vendor's engine (a full-book screening = the cs11 batch lane's biggest-ever job, scheduled across weeks); 10 y × ~200k decisions of evidence to migrate or wrap.`,
    options: `1. Migrate evidence into the new platform: their format, their lock-in — repeating rv7.\n2. Evidence into the OWNED audit/evidence store (cs17), vendors stay replaceable: the strategic fix.\n3. Keep old platform read-only for its retention life: viable fallback where export fidelity fails — priced (licence tail) and negotiated.`,
    recommended: `Option 2 as the strategic move this crisis funds: **evidence sovereignty** — decisions, match data and case history migrate into the owned evidence platform (cs17) with integrity verification (counts, checksums, sampled deep comparisons, all evidenced); the new vendor receives only operational needs. **Matching transition**: shadow-run the new engine alongside the incumbent for a quarter (same inputs, compare hit sets — divergences analysed with compliance: some are quality improvements, some are calibration; the analysis IS the validation evidence regulators expect for a model change). **Re-baseline**: full-book screening against the new engine's lists pre-cutover (differences case-managed). **In-flight cases**: freeze-and-transition window per case cohort with continuity notes — an investigation must read coherently across the seam. **The ACL pays out**: the cs11 architecture swaps vendor adapters; orchestration, case management and evidence never knew the vendor's name.`,
    tradeoffs: `Shadow-quarter costs double licences — priced against the alternative (cutover on faith with a regulator watching). Evidence migration vs read-only tail is decided per fidelity test results — the fallback is planned, not improvised. The re-baseline generates a case spike (staffing planned).`,
    dataApis: `Migration entities: EvidenceMigrationBatch(verification status), ShadowComparison(divergence categories), CaseTransition(cohort, continuity note). The new vendor contract's technical schedule: export formats, quarterly export tests, quota/SLA terms, list-update contracts — the rv7 lessons as clauses.`,
    kafka: `The cs11 topics unchanged (the point of contracts); a temporary shadow-comparison stream; adapter cutover is a consumer-group switch with the old adapter draining.`,
    security: `Bulk evidence in motion = maximum-sensitivity data flow: encrypted transfer, integrity verification, access-audited staging, purge evidence from staging after; the incumbent's off-boarding (their copies of our data — contractual destruction with certificates).`,
    failures: `Export fidelity fails on a data class → the read-only-tail fallback activates for that class (licence negotiated NOW while leverage exists). Shadow shows quality regression in a list category → calibration workshops with the new vendor pre-cutover; cutover gates on the compliance-signed comparison. Incumbent cooperation decays → everything front-loaded: exports and assistance exercised in months 1–6, not 13–18.`,
    operations: `The seam date is operationally sacred: dashboards show which engine screened what; dual evidence retrieval tested; the first regulator request spanning the seam rehearsed before it happens.`,
    migration: `Timeline: months 1–3 contracts + export tests; 3–9 shadow-run + evidence migration; 9–12 re-baseline + case transitions; 12–15 cutover + old adapter drain; 15–18 incumbent off-boarding + destruction certificates. Rollback until cutover = stay on incumbent (the renewal quote is the priced fallback — painful, available).`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: evidence sovereignty via owned store (the never-again decision). ADR-2: shadow-quarter validation (model-change governance). ADR-3: front-loaded exit exercising (cooperation decay).`,
    followups: ['Which contract clause in the NEW deal matters most, given this experience?', 'The shadow-run shows 15% fewer hits — good news or bad? How do you find out?', 'Why is the read-only tail a negotiation NOW rather than a fallback later?'],
    rubric: ['Evidence sovereignty as the strategic outcome', 'Shadow validation with compliance-signed analysis', 'In-flight case continuity designed', 'Cooperation-decay front-loading', 'New contract encodes the lessons'] },

  { id: 'cs21', title: 'Global System with Data-Residency Restrictions', difficulty: 'Expert', banking: true,
    problem: `Design the bk49 scenario fully: a private bank operating in Switzerland, the EU, Singapore and the UK needs a unified client-service platform — while Swiss banking secrecy, EU GDPR, and Singapore residency rules each pin data differently, and group-level compliance still needs sanctions coverage across all of it.`,
    clarifying: ['Per-jurisdiction rules: storage, processing, ACCESS (staff location) restrictions?', 'Which functions genuinely need global views (compliance, risk) vs want them (marketing)?', 'Client multi-jurisdiction reality (Swiss client with Singapore accounts)?', 'Latency expectations per region?', 'Group sanctions obligations vs local secrecy — the legal collision map?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** full client servicing per region; group-level sanctions screening coverage; group risk aggregation (non-personal); cross-region client relationships handled lawfully.\n**NFR:** residency per jurisdiction incl. backups and DR sites; access controls by staff jurisdiction; global functions on minimised, lawful data flows; regional autonomy (a region operates through another region\'s outage); every cross-border flow documented with legal basis.\n**Constraint:** legal sign-off is a design-loop participant, not a final gate.`,
    scale: `4 regions × the b6 domain landscape — the multiplication is operational (4× deployments via shared IaC) not architectural; the architecture problem is the THIN global layer's design: what may cross borders, in what form.`,
    options: `1. Global platform with residency filters (rv-style bolt-on): fails access-restriction rules and auditability.\n2. Regional cells + designed global minimum: recommended.\n3. Fully independent regional banks: lawful, loses group functions the regulators REQUIRE (sanctions coverage).`,
    recommended: `**Regional cells**: each jurisdiction runs the full domain stack (party, account, payment, screening — cs9/cs11 per region) from shared IaC modules; data, processing, backups, DR pinned in-jurisdiction; staff access jurisdiction-scoped (ABAC on staff-location attributes). **The thin global layer** — each flow designed, minimised, legally based: (a) **global party directory**: privacy-preserving reference (hashed identifiers + region pointers) enabling "does this person exist elsewhere in the group?" without moving personal data; (b) **group sanctions coverage**: screening runs IN-region against group-managed list content (lists flow inward — no client data flows outward); group compliance receives coverage attestations + anonymised metrics, drilling into a region only via that region's legal gateway (documented request, local approval, audited); (c) **group risk**: aggregated, non-personal exposures. **Multi-jurisdiction clients**: relationship records per region reference the directory; a Swiss client's Singapore accounts exist in Singapore, linked by reference, joined only under lawful process.`,
    tradeoffs: `Regional cells cost 4× operations (shared IaC + platform team makes it 4× deployments, not 4× engineering). The directory's hashed-reference design trades match quality (fuzzy matching on hashes is limited — a real limitation stated to compliance, mitigated by in-region matching against group lists). Group views are eventually consistent and minimised — executives wanting a "global client 360" hear the legal answer, with the lawful alternatives priced.`,
    dataApis: `Regional stacks per b6; global: DirectoryEntry(hashes, region pointers), CoverageAttestation, LegalGatewayRequest(basis, approvals, audit). Every cross-border API documented in the data-flow inventory (mo3) with basis — the inventory IS the regulator artifact.`,
    kafka: `Per-region clusters (residency binds brokers too); the global layer via explicit, minimal, contract-governed cross-region topics (list distribution inward; attestations outward); no casual mirroring — MirrorMaker is a data-transfer mechanism with legal meaning here.`,
    security: `Staff-jurisdiction ABAC everywhere; legal-gateway access with four-eyes + audit; per-region keys with in-jurisdiction custody (bk13); the threat model includes STATE-level actors for some jurisdictions — a sentence with infrastructure consequences (HSM custody, personnel vetting).`,
    failures: `Region outage → other regions unaffected (cell autonomy); group functions degrade gracefully (attestations lag, flagged). A lawful-basis change (adequacy decision revoked) → the affected flows are FINDABLE (the inventory) and switchable (designed minimisation means few flows to redesign). Cross-region client dispute → the legal-gateway process produces the joined view lawfully, evidenced.`,
    operations: `Per-region SRE with shared platform tooling; compliance dashboards per region + group coverage view; cross-border flow audits scheduled; game days include "regulator asks for the flow inventory" as a scenario.`,
    migration: `Region-by-region rollout (Switzerland first — strictest rules; if the design satisfies Swiss secrecy, the others inherit); existing global-ish systems' data REPATRIATED per classification (a migration wave per region with legal sign-off per data class).`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: cells over filtered-global (access-restriction rules decide, not preference). ADR-2: hashed directory (existence-checking without transfer). ADR-3: lists-inward screening (coverage without client-data export). ADR-4: legal gateway as designed process (exceptional access lawful by construction).`,
    followups: ['Group marketing wants global client analytics — walk the answer.', 'A Swiss client opens a UK account — trace the data flows and their bases.', 'Why does DR placement need the same residency analysis as production?'],
    rubric: ['Access restrictions (not just storage) drove the cell design', 'Global layer minimised with per-flow legal basis', 'Sanctions coverage achieved without client-data export', 'Multi-jurisdiction clients lawfully linked', 'Flow inventory as first-class artifact'] },

  { id: 'cs22', title: 'AI-Assisted Customer-Support Platform', difficulty: 'Advanced', banking: true,
    problem: `Add AI assistance to the bank's customer support: an LLM-based assistant drafting agent responses, summarising case histories, and (carefully) self-serving simple queries — inside banking's control, privacy and auditability regime. The m10 lesson as a build.`,
    clarifying: ['Which interactions may be fully automated vs draft-for-agent?', 'Data boundaries: what may reach the model (hosted where)?', 'Hallucination tolerance per use case (a wrong balance is not a typo)?', 'Evidence expectations for AI-involved interactions?', 'Fallback and escalation paths?'],
    requirements: `**Functional:** agent-assist (drafts, summaries, knowledge retrieval); customer self-service for a governed intent list; escalation to humans; feedback capture for improvement.\n**NFR:** zero customer-data leakage to ungoverned model endpoints; grounded answers only for factual queries (no hallucinated balances — retrieval-required); every AI-involved interaction reproducible (prompt, context, model version, output, human edits); latency: assist < 3 s, self-serve < 5 s; measurable quality gates before each automation expansion.\n**Constraint:** model endpoints must satisfy residency + data-processing terms (private/EU-hosted inference or contractual equivalents — legal in the loop).`,
    scale: `50k support interactions/day; assist on all = model traffic ~600/s peak tokens-heavy → inference cost is a first-class NFR (m4 applies: cost per assisted interaction tracked vs handle-time savings).`,
    options: `1. Agent-assist only (human always sends): lowest risk, immediate value — the starting point.\n2. + Governed self-service intents (balance queries, card blocks) with deterministic tool-calling: the expansion path.\n3. Open-ended customer chatbot: not in a bank. Stated and rejected with reasons (uncontrolled generation to customers fails the hallucination-tolerance analysis).`,
    recommended: `**Architecture**: a **deterministic contract around every model call** (m10): the orchestrator retrieves grounded context (knowledge base with citations, case history, CUSTOMER DATA ONLY per entitlement and minimisation), assembles governed prompts (templates versioned), calls the inference endpoint (private/contracted), **validates outputs** (schema for tool-calls; citation-required for factual claims; toxicity/PII filters), and routes: draft → agent (human sends, edits captured as feedback), self-serve intents → **deterministic tool execution** (the LLM classifies and extracts; the ACTION runs through the same governed APIs a human would use — the model never touches money directly), uncertain → human escalation with context. **Evidence**: every interaction logs prompt hash, context refs, model + template versions, output, human edits — the audit domain consumes it (cs17). **Quality loop**: eval suites (golden questions per intent) gate every model/prompt change; agent-edit rates and escalation rates trend quality; expansion of the automated-intent list is a governed release with compliance sign-off per intent.`,
    tradeoffs: `Draft-first sacrifices automation savings for controlled learning (the eval corpus and edit data BUILD the case for expansion — evidence-driven automation). Retrieval-required grounding constrains the assistant to what the knowledge base covers (coverage gaps route to humans — honest, measured). Private inference costs more per token than public endpoints; the alternative fails legal, so the comparison is theatre — priced anyway for the record.`,
    dataApis: `Entities: Interaction(evidence bundle), PromptTemplate(version), IntentPolicy(automation tier, sign-off), EvalRun, KnowledgeDoc(citation anchors). APIs: assist endpoints for the agent desktop, self-serve channel integration, eval workbench, intent governance workflow.`,
    kafka: `interaction.events.v1 (evidence to audit); feedback.v1 (edits, outcomes → eval corpus); knowledge-update events triggering re-indexing; NO customer-context caching in the pipeline beyond policy (minimisation).`,
    security: `Prompt injection is a real attack path (customer text reaches the model): input isolation in templates, output validation, tool-call allowlists (the model requests, policy disposes); data minimisation per call (entitlement-scoped retrieval — the model sees what THIS agent may see, never more); model endpoints in the vendor-risk regime (a4) incl. no-training-on-our-data clauses.`,
    failures: `Model endpoint down → assist degrades to knowledge-base search (agents worked without AI last year; the platform must too); self-serve falls back to menu flows. Hallucination reaches a customer despite gates → incident + eval-suite addition (every escape becomes a permanent test); the draft-first tier makes this an agent-caught event in the common case. Eval regression on a model upgrade → the gate blocks it; vendor model deprecations tracked like any dependency.`,
    operations: `Dashboards: assist adoption, edit distance (quality proxy), escalation rates, cost per interaction, eval pass rates per intent; the intent-expansion pipeline (candidate → eval corpus → shadow → sign-off → enable) is the operating rhythm.`,
    migration: `Agent-assist pilot (one support team, measured) → fleet rollout → self-serve intents one at a time by evidence; each expansion reversible by flag.`,
    adrs: `ADR-1: deterministic wrapper + tool-calling (the model never acts directly). ADR-2: draft-first with edit capture (evidence-driven automation). ADR-3: retrieval-grounded factual answers (hallucination containment). ADR-4: private inference (legal constraint; cost accepted).`,
    followups: ['A customer asks the assistant for their balance — trace the exact data flow and controls.', 'How do you prove to the regulator what the AI told customers last quarter?', 'The vendor deprecates your model version with 60 days notice — walk the response.'],
    rubric: ['Deterministic contract around model calls', 'Model never executes actions directly', 'Evidence bundle per interaction', 'Eval-gated, sign-off-governed expansion', 'Prompt injection + minimisation handled'] }
  ]);
})(window.SAA.data);
